k:80/person/CA39B8A1-C996-42AA-B649-B0D1F2E5839F"><gtr:id>CA39B8A1-C996-42AA-B649-B0D1F2E5839F</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>William</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Brian</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Thompson</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE016863%2F1"><gtr:id>EFDBE5ED-271B-4BE9-BF0A-33B86284FFED</gtr:id><gtr:title>Public Services Ombudsmen and Administrative Justice: Models, Roles, Methods and Relationships</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E016863/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Public service ombudsmen have a&amp;nbsp;statutory duty to investigate claims of injustice caused by maladministration in the provision of public services- central and local government and the NHS. This project will establish how this duty is&amp;nbsp;currently interpreted&amp;nbsp; by the ombudsmen and make recommendations as to how they might optimise their potential within the wider administrative justice context and develop new theoretical models of ombudsmen and their work.&lt;/p> 
&lt;p>The study will focus on the main roles of redressing complaints and improving administration, the methods which they&amp;nbsp;use and are&amp;nbsp;developing,&amp;nbsp;and their relationships&amp;nbsp;with other stakeholders in the emerging administrative justice system which includes the public, the public services agencies, the courts, internal complaints systems, tribunals, auditors,&amp;nbsp;elected representatives and advisory bodies.&lt;/p> 
&lt;p>The project team while concentrating on public services ombudsmen throughout the UK will also study their counterparts in Australia, Ireland and New Zealand. These countries&amp;nbsp;have arrangements which are broadly similar but have some differences which should help illuminate key issues.&amp;nbsp;The project team will interview the&amp;nbsp;ombudsmen&amp;nbsp; and a selection of parliamentarians, auditors and advisory bodies. Interviewees in the UK will also include other complaints handling bodies dealing with the police and prisons, child support and&amp;nbsp;tax.&lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-06-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>72528</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/6B8ADB6A-6EF4-4AA3-BFC6-F39622D510BE"><gtr:id>6B8ADB6A-6EF4-4AA3-BFC6-F39622D510BE</gtr:id><gtr:title>Putting the Ombudsman into Constitutional Context</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Parliamentary Affairs</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/306399f1ecae42597d7721db4660be51"><gtr:id>306399f1ecae42597d7721db4660be51</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Kirkham R</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2009-01-01</gtr:date></gtr:publication><gtr:publication ur